<div id="comments" class="comments-area">

			<h2 class="comments-title">
			6 thoughts on &ldquo;Deadline&rdquo;		</h2>

		
		<ol class="comment-list">
					<li id="comment-1161" class="comment even thread-even depth-1 parent">
			<article id="div-comment-1161" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/4744090ab36c8bcf5002046a9cf58456?s=56&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/4744090ab36c8bcf5002046a9cf58456?s=112&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-56 photo' height='56' width='56' />						<b class="fn">parfles</b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="http://localhost:8888/microfiction.co.za/2011/01/19/deadline/#comment-1161">
							<time datetime="2011-01-19T17:31:35+00:00">
								January 19, 2011 at 5:31 pm							</time>
						</a>
											</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>I love the idea &#8211; transferring the business babble to an alien setting, and making the whole thing a lot more overtly evil &#8211; no double speak here or political correctness. The scaly boss works well, and the pointless bureaucracy is highlighted in its alienness.</p>
<p>I also really like the little alien details that come out all over the place, the characterisations of all the different race &#8211; over the top and cute.</p>
<p>I found the first reading slightly difficult &#8211; a little too dense, and the information was packaged in such a way that I sometimes could not tell if I had missed something or if the information wasn&#8217;t given to me on purpose. On second reading, much fewer qualms.</p>
<p>I have some minor suggestions :</p>
<p>&#8211; &#8220;The head of the Thrust Team limped to the front, his carapace still blackened from the testing incident, and said,&#8221; &#8211; you could try the paragraph without the &#8220;and said&#8221; &#8211; the meaning will remain clear.</p>
<p>&#8211;  ‚ÄúUnfortunately all engineering and design specialists have been removed from the Steering Committee in order to streamline the product-to-market process. So I never told them (&#8230;)&#8221; &#8211; I&#8217;m not sure how the &#8220;so I never told them&#8221; follows from the preceding phrase.</p>
<p>&#8211; ‚ÄúDue to the cost in equipment and danger to key personnel all future thrust testing &#8221; &#8211; I would suggest a comma after &#8220;future&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;Timidly the new intern raised a vivid orange pseudo-tentacle&#8221; &#8211; If you want that adverb up front, I would say it needs a comma after it. But something like &#8220;The new intern raised a timid orange pseudo-tentacle&#8221; may work better?</p>
<p>&#8211; The capitalisation of Steering Committee is inconsistent.</p>
<p>That seems like an awful number of nitpicks, but that is all they are &#8211; very small nitpicks to a very fun alien encounter. </p>
<p>If I have one regret it&#8217;s that I don&#8217;t know what the product is &#8211; I would have liked to have found it&#8217;s the starting kernel for our universe or something familiar that would tie up with the f*ck up of its creation&#8230; <img src="http://localhost:8888/microfiction.co.za/wp-includes/images/smilies/simple-smile.png" alt=":)" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /></p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

				<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='http://localhost:8888/microfiction.co.za/2011/01/19/deadline/?replytocom=1161#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "div-comment-1161", "1161", "respond", "689" )' aria-label='Reply to parfles'>Reply</a></div>			</article><!-- .comment-body -->
